@Youssef1313 

> This is by-design, I think. When you do an explicit (a.k.a pure) null check, the variable/local state is changed to maybe null.

I'm not sure that designing in side effects is a good option. Merely observing an object's state should not change it. Imagine you had the following with a bool that's value gets changed simply using it in an if statement. The result could be disastrous.

```
bool engineHasOil = true;
if (engineHasOil) // Using the if statement changes engineHasOil to false
