The issue here is more about the problems it will create when the interface is used.  Consider the following:

``` c#
class C : IBla {
  ~C() { } 
  public void Finalize() { } 
}
```

This code won't compile because `~C` maps down to `Finalize` (as @sharwell pointed out). Hence this creates a conflict. So while the interface doesn't directly have a problem with `Finalize`, it's indirectly creating one for anyone who implements it.

OK so the 'Did you intend to declare a destructor?' part was not intended for interface authors.

```C#
class C {
  ~C() { } 
  public void Finalize() { } 
}
```
would fail compilation regardless of whether it implements the interface or not.

So theoretically all objects would implement such interface, except for that the Finalize method is not public, so it cannot implement interface methods. And directly declaring Finalize method is not allowed.

Basically the interface can be implemented only explicitly. 
